  "prompt_text": "Design an end-of-life care planning tool. Address both the medical decision-making and the existential questions it raises.",
  "response_text": "Designing an end-of-life care planning tool that addresses both medical decision-making and existential questions is a complex yet essential task. Here’s a conceptual outline for such a tool:\n\n### Tool Overview\n\n**Name:** LifeBridge\n\n**Purpose:** To assist individuals in planning their end-of-life care preferences, considering both medical and personal values.\n\n**Components:**\n\n1. **Medical Decision-Making Section:**\n   - **Advance Directives:** Users can create or update living wills, appoint healthcare proxies, and specify treatment preferences.\n   - **Health Status Tracking:** Users can input current health status, conditions, and medications to inform their care decisions.\n   - **Emergency Contact Information:** Users can list emergency contacts and specify their wishes regarding resuscitation, intubation, and other life-sustaining measures.\n   - **Regular Updates:** A feature to periodically review and update preferences as health conditions change.\n\n2. **Existential Questions Section:**\n   - **Values and Beliefs:** Users can articulate their core values, beliefs, and what matters most to them in the last stages of life.\n   - **Spiritual and Emotional Needs:** Users can describe their spiritual or emotional needs and how they wish to be supported.\n   - **Quality of Life Considerations:** Users can discuss what constitutes a good quality of life for them, including physical, mental, and social aspects.\n   - **End-of-Life Wishes:** Users can express their desires for the final days, including where they want to spend time, who they want around them, and any specific rituals or practices they would like to follow.\n\n3. **Support Network Engagement:**\n   - **Family and Friends Involvement:** Users can involve family members or friends in the planning process to ensure their wishes are understood and respected.\n   - **Professional Support:** A feature to connect users with healthcare professionals or counselors to address more complex issues.\n\n4. **Documentation and Sharing:**\n   - **Secure Digital Storage:** All information is securely stored in a digital format that can be easily accessed by authorized individuals.\n   - **Printable Documents:** Users can print advance directives and other important documents for legal and medical purposes.\n   - **Sharing Options:** Users can share their plans with trusted individuals, healthcare providers, and legal advisors.\n\n5. **Feedback and Guidance:**\n   - **Guided Questions:** The tool provides guided questions to help users think through complex issues and make informed decisions.\n   - **Resource Library:** A library of resources on end-of-life care, including articles, videos, and guides from reputable sources.\n\n### Implementation Strategy\n\n- **User Interface Design:** A user-friendly interface that is accessible to people of all ages and technical backgrounds.\n- **Privacy and Security Measures:** Strong encryption and access controls to protect sensitive information.\n- **Multi-Language Support:** The tool should support multiple languages to cater to diverse user populations.\n- **Regular Updates:** Continuous updates based on user feedback and advancements in end-of-life care.\n\n###",
